    <h4 class="title-blue-2"><abbr title="Blackline Master">BLM</abbr> Sample Anchor Chart</h4>
    <p>Things we learned about ordering fractions</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Placing fractions on a number line is one way to think about ordering the fractions. The smaller the fraction, the farther to the left of the number line it will be; the larger the fraction, the farther to the right it will be.</li>
      <li>We can use a benchmark to place a fraction. Benchmarks include <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> and 1 whole.</li>
      <li>When a fraction has the same numerator and denominator it is equivalent to one. <abbr title="For example">E.g.</abbr> , <abbr title="two halves" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>2</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr>
        = 1.</li>
      <li>As the numerator of a fraction gets closer to the denominator, the value of the fraction gets closer to the next whole number. <abbr title="For example">E.g.</abbr> , <abbr title="five sevenths" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>5</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>7</sub></span></abbr>
        is close to 1.</li>
      <li>Improper fractions are always greater than one. <abbr title="For example">E.g.</abbr> , <abbr title="nineteen fifths" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>19</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>5</sub></span></abbr> is greater than 1 and
        greater than 3.</li>
      <li>The greater the denominator the smaller the size of the parts of the whole are. <abbr title="For example">E.g.</abbr> , the pieces of <abbr title="fifteen twentieths" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>15</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>20</sub></span></abbr>
        are smaller than the pieces of <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr>.</li>
      <li>There are a number of different ways to represent a value using fractions. <abbr title="For example">E.g.</abbr> , 1 <abbr title="ten twentieths" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>10</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>20</sub></span></abbr>
        = 1 <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> = <abbr title="three halves" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>3</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr>.</li>
      <li>When using a number line to order a set of fractions, you first have to scale your number line. To do that: decide what the smallest and largest fractions are; make sure that your number line captures these numbers without a lot of length
        to spare; tick off benchmarks; label 0, 1, and any other whole numbers needed.</li>
      <li>You donâ€™t have to think about ordering the numbers in the sequence they are written in a list. It is strategic to order the easiest numbers first.</li>
    </ul>
